import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.dates as mdates

# Load the data
file_path = r'C:\Users\eterra\Desktop\pt\anaconda\S&P 500 Historical Data.csv'
df = pd.read_csv(file_path, delimiter=';')
df.columns = [col.strip() for col in df.columns]

# Clean numeric columns
for col in df.columns[1:]:
    df[col] = df[col].astype(str).str.replace(',', '', regex=False).str.replace(' ', '', regex=False).str.replace('%', '', regex=False)
    df[col] = pd.to_numeric(df[col], errors='coerce')

# Convert date column
df['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Date'], format='%m/%d/%Y')  # U.S. format: MM/DD/YYYY
df = df.sort_values('Date')

# Calculate financial metrics
df['Daily Return'] = df['Price'].pct_change()
df['MA20'] = df['Price'].rolling(window=20).mean()
df['MA50'] = df['Price'].rolling(window=50).mean()
df['Rolling Volatility (30d)'] = df['Daily Return'].rolling(window=30).std()

# Set plotting style
plt.style.use('ggplot')
font = {'size': 12}
plt.rc('font', **font)
locator = mdates.YearLocator()
formatter = mdates.DateFormatter('%Y')

# -------------------------------
# GRAPH 1: Distribution of Daily Returns
# -------------------------------
#### This histogram shows the frequency of daily returns.
## Formula used: Daily Return = (Price_t / Price_{t-1}) - 1
## It gives insight into the risk/return profile, identifying the spread of gains/losses.
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.hist(df['Daily Return'].dropna(), bins=50, edgecolor='white', color='#4a90e2', alpha=0.9)
plt.title('Distribution of Daily Returns', fontsize=18, fontweight='bold', pad=15)
plt.xlabel('Daily Return', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('Frequency', fontsize=14)
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', linewidth=0.5, alpha=0.7)
plt.xticks(fontsize=12)
plt.yticks(fontsize=12)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()


# -------------------------------
# GRAPH 2: Price with Moving Averages
# -------------------------------
## This time series plot shows the index and two moving averages.
## Formulas used:
##    MA20_t = (1/20) * sum(Price_{t-19} ... Price_t)
##    MA50_t = (1/50) * sum(Price_{t-49} ... Price_t)
## Helps identify short- and medium-term market trends and momentum
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 7))
plt.plot(df['Date'], df['Price'], label='S&P 500 Price', linewidth=2.5, color='#2c3e50')
plt.plot(df['Date'], df['MA20'], label='20-Day MA', linestyle='--', linewidth=2, color='#27ae60')
plt.plot(df['Date'], df['MA50'], label='50-Day MA', linestyle='-.', linewidth=2, color='#e67e22')
plt.title('S&P 500 Price with 20 & 50-Day Moving Averages', fontsize=18, fontweight='bold', pad=15)
plt.xlabel('Date', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('Index Price', fontsize=14)
plt.legend(fontsize=12, loc='upper left')
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', linewidth=0.5, alpha=0.7)
plt.xticks(fontsize=12)
plt.yticks(fontsize=12)
plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(locator)
plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_formatter(formatter)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()


# -------------------------------
# GRAPH 3: Rolling Volatility (30-Day Std Dev)
# -------------------------------
## This plot shows how volatility evolves over time.
## Formula used:
##    Volatility_t = std(Daily_Return_{t-29}, ..., Daily_Return_t)
## Measures the market's uncertainty and risk over a 30-day window.
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 6))
plt.plot(df['Date'], df['Rolling Volatility (30d)'], color='#c0392b', linewidth=2.5)
plt.title('30-Day Rolling Volatility of S&P 500', fontsize=18, fontweight='bold', pad=15)
plt.xlabel('Date', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('Volatility (Standard Deviation)', fontsize=14)
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', linewidth=0.5, alpha=0.7)
plt.xticks(fontsize=12)
plt.yticks(fontsize=12)
plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(locator)
plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_formatter(formatter)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.dates as mdates

# -------------------------------
# LOAD & CLEAN DATA
# -------------------------------
file_path = r'C:\Users\eterra\Desktop\pt\anaconda\S&P 500 Historical Data.csv'
df = pd.read_csv(file_path, delimiter=';')
df.columns = [col.strip() for col in df.columns]

# Clean numeric columns safely
for col in df.columns[1:]:
    df[col] = df[col].astype(str)
    df[col] = df[col].str.replace(',', '', regex=False)
    df[col] = df[col].str.replace(' ', '', regex=False)
    df[col] = df[col].str.replace('%', '', regex=False)
    df[col] = pd.to_numeric(df[col], errors='coerce')

# Convert dates (US format: MM/DD/YYYY)
df['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Date'], format='%m/%d/%Y', errors='coerce')
df = df.sort_values('Date')

# -------------------------------
# CALCULATIONS
# -------------------------------
df['Daily Return'] = df['Price'].pct_change()
df['Cumulative Return'] = (1 + df['Daily Return']).cumprod()
df['Cumulative Max'] = df['Cumulative Return'].cummax()
df['Drawdown'] = (df['Cumulative Return'] - df['Cumulative Max']) / df['Cumulative Max']

# -------------------------------
# PLOT 1: Cumulative Return
## This graph shows the growth of a hypothetical $1 investment over time.
## It's calculated by compounding daily returns: (1 + return_1) * (1 + return_2) * ...
## It helps visualize the long-term performance of the S&P 500.
# -------------------------------
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 6))
plt.plot(df['Date'], df['Cumulative Return'], color='#2ca02c', linewidth=2)
plt.title('Cumulative Return of S&P 500', fontsize=18, fontweight='bold')
plt.xlabel('Date', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Growth of $1', fontsize=12)
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(mdates.YearLocator(2))
plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_formatter(mdates.DateFormatter('%Y'))
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# -------------------------------
# PLOT 2: Drawdown (Risk)
## This graph shows drawdowns: how far the index has fallen from previous peaks.
## It's a key risk measure in finance, capturing worst-case declines during crashes.
## Calculated as: (current value - max value so far) / max value so far.
# -------------------------------
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 6))
plt.fill_between(df['Date'], df['Drawdown'], color='firebrick', alpha=0.4)
plt.plot(df['Date'], df['Drawdown'], color='firebrick', linewidth=1.5)
plt.title('Drawdown from Historical Peaks', fontsize=18, fontweight='bold')
plt.xlabel('Date', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Drawdown (%)', fontsize=12)
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(mdates.YearLocator(2))
plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_formatter(mdates.DateFormatter('%Y'))
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# -------------------------------
# TABLE: Yearly Performance Summary
## Annual Return = (End Price / Start Price - 1) * 100
## Annualized Volatility = Std(Daily Return) * sqrt(252)
## This summary shows annual returns and volatility of the S&P 500.
## Volatility is the annualized standard deviation of daily returns.
## This table is useful to assess performance and risk by year.
# -------------------------------
df['Year'] = df['Date'].dt.year
yearly = df.groupby('Year').agg(
    Start_Price=('Price', 'first'),
    End_Price=('Price', 'last'),
    Mean_Return=('Daily Return', 'mean'),
    Volatility=('Daily Return', 'std')
)
yearly['Yearly Return (%)'] = (yearly['End_Price'] / yearly['Start_Price'] - 1) * 100
yearly['Annualized Volatility (%)'] = yearly['Volatility'] * (252**0.5) * 100
yearly = yearly[['Yearly Return (%)', 'Annualized Volatility (%)']].round(2)

# Print summary table
print("\nYearly Performance Summary:")
print(yearly)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.dates as mdates
from pandas.plotting import autocorrelation_plot
import numpy as np

# -------------------------------
# ANALYSIS 1: 30-Day Rolling Sharpe Ratio
# -------------------------------

df['Rolling Mean Return'] = df['Daily Return'].rolling(window=30).mean()
df['Rolling Volatility'] = df['Daily Return'].rolling(window=30).std()
df['Rolling Sharpe Ratio'] = df['Rolling Mean Return'] / df['Rolling Volatility']

plt.figure(figsize=(14, 6))
plt.plot(df['Date'], df['Rolling Sharpe Ratio'], color='#1f77b4', linewidth=2.5)
plt.title('30-Day Rolling Sharpe Ratio of S&P 500', fontsize=18, fontweight='bold', pad=15)
plt.xlabel('Date', fontsize=13)
plt.ylabel('Sharpe Ratio', fontsize=13)
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', linewidth=0.5, alpha=0.5)
plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(mdates.YearLocator(2))
plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_formatter(mdates.DateFormatter('%Y'))
plt.xticks(rotation=45, fontsize=11)
plt.yticks(fontsize=11)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# -------------------------------
# ANALYSIS 2: Histogram of Volatility (5-Day Rolling Std)
# -------------------------------

volatility_values = df['Daily Return'].rolling(window=5).std()

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.hist(volatility_values.dropna(), bins=50, color='#ff7f0e', edgecolor='white', alpha=0.85)
plt.title('Histogram of 5-Day Rolling Volatility', fontsize=18, fontweight='bold', pad=15)
plt.xlabel('5-Day Std Dev of Returns', fontsize=13)
plt.ylabel('Frequency', fontsize=13)
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', linewidth=0.5, alpha=0.5)
plt.xticks(fontsize=11)
plt.yticks(fontsize=11)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# -------------------------------
# ANALYSIS 3: Autocorrelation of Daily Returns
# -------------------------------

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Data prep
returns = df['Daily Return'].dropna()
max_lags = len(returns) - 1

# Compute all autocorrelations
acf_values = [returns.autocorr(lag=i) for i in range(max_lags)]

# Confidence bounds (approximation under white noise)
conf_bound = 1.96 / np.sqrt(len(returns))

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 6))
plt.plot(acf_values, color='orangered', linewidth=0.8, alpha=0.8, label='Autocorrelation')
plt.axhline(0, color='black', linewidth=1)
plt.axhline(conf_bound, linestyle='--', color='gray', linewidth=1, label='Confidence Bounds (±1.96/√N)')
plt.axhline(-conf_bound, linestyle='--', color='gray', linewidth=1)

# Styling
plt.title('Autocorrelation of Daily Returns (All Lags)', fontsize=18, fontweight='bold', pad=15)
plt.xlabel('Lag (Days)', fontsize=13)
plt.ylabel('Autocorrelation', fontsize=13)
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', linewidth=0.5, alpha=0.4)
plt.xticks(fontsize=11)
plt.yticks(fontsize=11)
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
